r","meanings":["English: variant of   Bowler  . The surname is unlikely to have been derived from Middle English <i>buller(e)</i> ‘maker or publisher of bulls or papal edicts’. It is recorded only in the phrase <i>fals buller</i> ‘publisher of false bulls’. Old French <i>boleor</i>, <i>bouleur</i>, from which the word was borrowed, more generally meant ‘deceiver, trickster’, so possibly it also had this sense in Middle English but there is no evidence for it.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Bullard  .","German (also <b>Büller</b>): nickname for a man with a loud voice, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>büllen</i> ‘to roar, to bark’ (of imitative origin)."]}]},{"name":"Ermentrude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, adopted from Old French by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It is derived from <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’ + <i>traut</i> ‘beloved’. It did not survive long into the Middle Ages, but was occasionally revived in the 18th and 19th centuries. It is now completely out of fashion."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ermentrude DE BULLES was born in 1140, in Bulles, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Renaud Beauvais De Bulles, was 20 and her mother, Euphémie de Picquigny, was 22. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Guillaume II DE MELLO. She died in Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France."},"et":{"1140–":"1140–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1165–1224":"1165–1224","1180–1245":"1180–1245","1120–1165":"1120–1165","1118–1160":"1118–1160","1118":"1118","1190":"1190","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1201":"1201","1135":"1135","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Bulles, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Bulles, Oise, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Mello